<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="chemistry">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Chemistry.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Thallus K-, C+. Medulla I+ violet. Gyrophoric acid.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Ecology and distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">In China, growing on granite at elevations of 1400-2000 m in steppe or mountains. This species is known from Inner Mongolia of China.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="99" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="99">
This species was once reported as &quot; 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rambold &amp; Pietschm., Bibliotheca Lichenologica 34: 239" authorityYear="1989" class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Lecideaceae" genus="Immersaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Immersaria" order="Lecideales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Immersaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
&quot; 
<taxonomicName class="Lecanoromycetes" family="Lecideaceae" genus="Immersaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Immersaria cupreoatra" order="Lecideales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="cupreoatra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Immersaria cupreoatra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from China (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5248/130.899" author="Zhang, LL" journalOrPublisher="Mycotaxon, Ithaca NY," pageId="0" pageNumber="99" pagination="899 - 905" refId="B26" refString="Zhang, LL, Hu, L, Zhao, XX, Zhao, ZT, 2015. New records of Clauzadea and Immersaria from China. Mycotaxon, Ithaca NY, 130 (3): 899 - 905, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5248/130.899" title="New records of Clauzadea and Immersaria from China." url="https://doi.org/10.5248/130.899" volume="130" year="2015">Zhang et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
), but after comparing our collections with the type material, this was found to be a misclassification. Additionally, the phylogenetic results showed that these collections formed a well-supported lineage belonging to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. M. Xie, Lu L. Zhang &amp; Li S. Wang" authorityYear="2022" family="Lecideaceae" genus="Lecaimmeria" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Lecaimmeria" order="Lecideales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Lecaimmeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, it is here treated as a new species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. M. Xie &amp; Lu L. Zhang" authorityYear="2022" family="Lecideaceae" genus="Lecaimmeria" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Lecaimmeria mongolica" order="Lecideales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="mongolica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Lecaimmeria mongolica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, characterised by its orange-brown thallus, red-brown apothecia with a distinct white margin and the thallus containing gyrophoric acid. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. M. Xie" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="C. M. Xie" baseAuthorityYear="2022" family="Lecideaceae" genus="Lecaimmeria" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Lecaimmeria cupreoatra" order="Lecideales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="cupreoatra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Lecaimmeria cupreoatra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. mongolica" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="mongolica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">L. mongolica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by containing gyrophoric acid, but it differs in its dark black brown thallus and the black margin of its apothecia. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C. M. Xie &amp; Xin Y. Wang" authorityYear="2022" family="Lecideaceae" genus="Lecaimmeria" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Lecaimmeria tibetica" order="Lecideales" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="tibetica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">Lecaimmeria tibetica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="L." lsidName="L. mongolica" pageId="0" pageNumber="99" rank="species" species="mongolica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="99">L. mongolica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its orange thallus, but differs in its smaller, dark orange apothecia and that no substance can be detected by TLC.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
